    <segment id="1" parent="22" relname="preparation">


I agree with P19 about many of the attributes he mentioned.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="16" relname="antithesis"> I believe there are certain guidelines that can help with the development,</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="20" relname="span"> but that website development needs to be an iterative process and that testing is important to making sure these attributes can be achieved.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="13" relname="conjunction"> 
Unfortunately many designers work with systems the general users don&apos;t have</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="13" relname="conjunction"> and they may be on a high-speed network,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="13" relname="volitional-result"> so from thier point of view response time is acceptable.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="10" relname="circumstance"> But as soon as that site is accessed by users with dial-up access</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="14" relname="span"> troubles begin with response time.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="11" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> 
Also it seems that many developers create pages using new large screens</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="17" relname="span"> and then when users access the page it overflows their screen.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="17" relname="evaluation"> As a web user, I never want to scroll right as well as down to read a web page.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="12" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> 
There are a lot of variables in web design,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="21" relname="span"> so it is important to consider these variables in the design process and to test, test, test with the expected users in mind.</segment>
